  "text": "Sox2 þ cells continued to express Sox2 in culture. However, Sox2 was not induced to a significant extent in Sox2À cells, either in culture or following engraftment. In addition, Sox2 was not induced in new hair follicles that formed as a result of b-catenin activation in adult epidermis. These observations are consistent with Sox2 þ and Sox2À cells representing distinct cell lineages that are specified during skin development (Driskell et al., 2009 ). Our findings are also consistent with the finding that Sox2 is a marker of multipotent dermal stem cells that reside in the DP and contribute extensively to the dermis following wounding [CITATION_1] . Sox2 þ cells represent only 1% of neonatal dermal cells [CITATION_2] , and it has not, therefore, been possible to obtain sufficient cells to test their contribution to reconstituted skin in the absence of unfractionated, helper cells [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . One strategy that could potentially overcome this hurdle is to expand Sox2 þ cells on tissue culture plastic before hydrogel encapsulation.",
